ce:section.ce:para:
The construction of nanostructures is considered to be an effective ways to improve the sodium storage performance of anode materials [16,17]. Among numerous nanostructures, two-dimensional porous ultrathin nanosheets have attracted much attention due to their exposure to more active sites, ion channels, and interface boundaries, which can reduce the length of electron and ion transport paths [18–21]. The porous structure enables buffering of volume expansion, thereby enhancing the characterization of nanostructure stabilization [22,23]. At present, the peeling strategy and direct chemical synthesis strategy are mainly used to prepare ultrathin ZnSe nanosheets. However, constructing ultrathin ZnSe nanosheets with carbon coating, Se vacancy, and porous structure is a great challenge, mainly because it is difficult to maintain the ultrathin structure after the traditional carbon coating method, and the construction of Se vacancy and porous structure is easy to cause the ultrathin nanosheet structure collapse. In recent years, a class of organic–inorganic hybrid materials [MQ(L)
                        x
                     ] (M=Zn, Cd; Q=S, Se or Te; L=organic amine molecule) has attracted extensive research interest as an excellent precursor for the preparation of selenides nanosheets due to its well-ordered structure and adjustable thickness [24–28]. In this hybrid structure, the organic part of the amine molecules is periodically and orderly embedded in the inorganic part of the selenide, forming thickness-controllable nanosheets. After carbonization, the organic amines can be grown in situ as carbon materials to form composite materials with selenides, and at the same time, the structure of porous ultrathin nanosheets can be constructed. Mahadik et al. [29] transformed CdSe(en)0.5 nanostructures into CdSe nanowires/nanosheets by in situ hydrothermal-processing. Zhu et al. [25] used ZnS(butylamine) nanosheets as precursors to prepare porous ZnS nanosheets via a chemical transformation strategy. Ma et al. [30] synthesized ZnS·(DETA)0.5 hybrid precursors to prepare functional ZnS and carbon-encapsulated sulfur (S@C) nanomaterial cathodes for Li-S batteries.
